{"id":14881856,"mediaExerciseId":"afbf0362-5b14-4ab0-82e3-08eeec53426e","exerciseName":"6","chapterName":"24","chapterTitle":"Options and Corporate Finance","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"24.6","sectionTitle":"Options and Capital Budgeting","pageNumber":814,"solutions":[{"id":6006203,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will learn about capital budgeting proposal, options to expand, abandon, and suspend operations, and strategic options.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/8767c82378289b78734f1af63d6e1819/dc1414e8b8ed6c38894f713a2309d0ff/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/8767c82378289b78734f1af63d6e1819/dc1414e8b8ed6c38894f713a2309d0ff/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define capital budgeting.\n\n**Capital Budgeting** is a process that businesses undertake to determine which project or investment they should accept. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/8767c82378289b78734f1af63d6e1819/2a6cf3404848d8c046904b6647870c0c/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/8767c82378289b78734f1af63d6e1819/2a6cf3404848d8c046904b6647870c0c/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"### a. Why do we say that almost every capital budgeting proposal involves mutually exclusive alternatives.\n\nManagers can only choose to invest in one type of a project, therefore choosing one project excludes the other. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"### b.1. Option to expand\n\nThe option to expand reflects the capability of a firm to increase production if the new product sells more than what they initially expected.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"### b.2. Option to abandon\n\nThe option to abandon is an option to abandon a project if it has a negative or zero Net Present Value (NPV) and the company decides to give up the project completely because it cannot cover its expenses.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"### b.3. Option to suspend\n\nThe option to suspend is an option to shut down a project if the conditions are unfavorable and resume the operations when the conditions are favorable again.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"### c. Strategic options\n\nStrategic options are alternatives that companies have to explore possibilities and evaluate future business strategies.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"3b4e97bb-a51f-4a70-8fbd-81cfe1f9d6ce","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":7}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,